HEADWORD: Ineluctable
<hw>In`e*luc"ta*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ineluctabilis</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> not +
<ets>eluctabilis</ets> to be surmounted, fr. <ets>eluctari</ets> to
struggle out of, to surmount: cf. F. <ets>in⟦eacute⟧luctable</ets>. See
<er>Eluctate</er>.]</ety> <def>Not to be overcome by struggling;
irresistible; inescapable; inevitable.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Pearson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>ineluctable</qex> conditions of matter.</q>
<rj><qau>Hamerton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ineludible</ent>⟦br⟧
